"People choose this u . s . to be better," he informed CNN. "They want the money out of Washington," adding that he believed the U.S. government remains mostly controlled via corporations.
New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg said until now Friday that Brookfield Office Properties -- the real-estate company that owns Zuccotti Park, regarded a home-base for protesters -- made the choice now not to clear them out after the organization used to be "inundated" with threatening calls from elected city officials.
The mayor said throughout his weekly commentary on New York's WOR Radio that he didn't know which officers allegedly made the threats, but that the business enterprise decided to work out some form of a negotiated agreement with protesters in the coming days.
Bloomberg brought that whilst he lacked first-hand expertise of the conversations, he was instructed the officers typically threatened to "make existence extra difficult" for the real-estate company.
