"Our position has been steady throughout: the City's position is to protect public fitness and safety, to put in force the law, and assurance the rights of all New Yorkers. Brookfield believes they can work out an arrangement with the protesters that will ensure the park remains clean, safe, on hand for public use and that the situation is respectful of residents and groups downtown, and we will proceed to monitor the situation," stated Deputy Mayor Cas Holloway.
The demonstrations have been primarily peaceful, though there had been fears of a standoff between police officers tasked with clearing the park and protesters who stated they would not budge.
City officers in New York had in the beginning ordered the protesters to leave by 7 a.m.
But the demonstrators mopped, accumulated trash and scrubbed the pavement in the dead of the night time as the Friday closing date neared for them to go away the premises for a cleanup. When the word of the postponed cleansing filtered through the more than 1,000 protesters who crammed the park, they have been elated.
